content.problemStatement:
In Java, 2D arrays are stored in **row-major order**, where elements are processed row by row, optimizing row-wise traversal. In **column-major order**, elements are accessed column by column, but Java does not natively store arrays this way. Understanding these operations helps optimize performance, especially for large datasets.

**Syntax:**  

**Row-major Traversal:**  
```java
for (int i = 0; i < array.length; i++) {  // Iterate rows
    for (int j = 0; j < array[i].length; j++) {  // Iterate columns
        // Access array[i][j]
    }
}
```

**Column-major Traversal:**  
```java
for (int j = 0; j < array[0].length; j++) {  // Iterate columns
    for (int i = 0; i < array.length; i++) {  // Iterate rows
        // Access array[i][j]
    }
}
```

---

**Example:**  
```java
class Seedit {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Step 1: Declare and Initialize a 2D array
        int[][] matrix = {
            {1, 2, 3},
            {4, 5, 6},
            {7, 8, 9}
        };

        // Step 2: Row-major traversal
        System.out.println("Row-major Order:");
        for (int i = 0; i < matrix.length; i++) {  
            for (int j = 0; j < matrix[i].length; j++) {  
                System.out.print(matrix[i][j] + " ");  
            }
            System.out.println();
        }

        // Step 3: Column-major traversal
        System.out.println("Column-major Order:");
        for (int j = 0; j < matrix[0].length; j++) {  
            for (int i = 0; i < matrix.length; i++) {  
                System.out.print(matrix[i][j] + " ");  
            }
            System.out.println();
        }
    }
}
```
---

**Expected Output:**  
```default
Row-major Order:
1 2 3  
4 5 6  
7 8 9  

Column-major Order:
1 4 7  
2 5 8  
3 6 9  
```

